docs.abstract: The Fed chairman, Jerome H. Powell, did not mention President Trump on Wednesday, but his remarks amounted to a defense of the central bank.
docs.snippet: The Fed chairman, Jerome H. Powell, did not mention President Trump on Wednesday, but his remarks amounted to a defense of the central bank.
docs.lead_paragraph: DALLAS — Jerome H. Powell, the chairman of the Federal Reserve, on Wednesday countered President Trump’s loud and repeated attacks on the Fed without mentioning Mr. Trump by name.

headline.main: Powell Says Fed Deserves Credit for Economic Growth
headline.print_headline: Chairman Gives Credit to Fed For Role in Economy’s Growth

docs.abstract: The Continent faces a confluence of economic and political crises after Germany’s growth disappointed and Italy defied calls to modify a populist budget plan.
docs.snippet: The Continent faces a confluence of economic and political crises after Germany’s growth disappointed and Italy defied calls to modify a populist budget plan.
docs.lead_paragraph: BRUSSELS — Germany’s once unstoppable economy has gone into reverse, adding another threat to European stability just as Italy escalated its dispute with fiscal overseers in Brussels.

headline.main: German Economy Shrinks Unexpectedly, Adding to Europe’s Risk
headline.print_headline: Sudden Decline in German Economy Adds to Europe’s Risk

docs.abstract: The government’s efforts to help those who were defrauded by their schools have all but ground to a halt. Instead, it is fighting claims in court.
docs.snippet: The government’s efforts to help those who were defrauded by their schools have all but ground to a halt. Instead, it is fighting claims in court.
docs.lead_paragraph: The students attended institutions with pragmatic names like the Minnesota School of Business and others whose branding evoked ivy-draped buildings and leafy quads, like Corinthian Colleges. Tens of thousands of them say they are alike in one respect: They were victims of fraud, left with useless degrees and crushing debts.

headline.main: Borrowers Face Hazy Path as Program to Forgive Student Loans Stalls Under Betsy DeVos

docs.abstract: Chevron, the No. 2 energy producer in the United States, gains assets in shale oil drilling and liquefied natural gas by acquiring Anadarko, based in Texas.
docs.snippet: Chevron, the No. 2 energy producer in the United States, gains assets in shale oil drilling and liquefied natural gas by acquiring Anadarko, based in Texas.
docs.lead_paragraph: HOUSTON — Chevron positioned itself to become the dominant oil producer in the field that is driving the American shale revolution when it said on Friday that it was buying Anadarko Petroleum for $33 billion.

headline.main: Chevron to Acquire Anadarko Petroleum for $33 Billion, a Shift in the Battle for Shale
headline.print_headline: Chevron Says It Will Acquire Anadarko Petroleum for $33 Billion

docs.abstract: Uncertainty over the stability of a trade war truce between Washington and Beijing has renewed investor worries about global growth prospects.
docs.snippet: Uncertainty over the stability of a trade war truce between Washington and Beijing has renewed investor worries about global growth prospects.
docs.lead_paragraph: HONG KONG — Stocks around the world declined on Wednesday, a day after Mr. Trump posted a series of messages on Twitter warning that a fragile cease-fire in the trade war between the United States and China could be derailed. The drops in Asia and Europe came after stocks on Wall Street fell more than 3 percent on Tuesday.

headline.main: Global Markets Fall After a Wall Street Sell-Off Spurred by Trump Tweets

docs.abstract: Major stock indexes dropped again Friday, in Wall Street’s third decline this week. Investors remained gripped by uncertainty about how much the American economy could slow next year.
docs.snippet: Major stock indexes dropped again Friday, in Wall Street’s third decline this week. Investors remained gripped by uncertainty about how much the American economy could slow next year.
docs.lead_paragraph: Stocks on Wall Street dropped again Friday, pushing the S&P 500 into negative territory for the year, as investors continued to fixate on how much the economy and corporate profits could slow next year.

headline.main: Stocks Fall Back Into Negative Territory for 2018 as Economic Uncertainty Grips Investors
headline.print_headline: S&P Skids Back Into Negative Territory

docs.abstract: New figures suggest the Chinese slowdown is bottoming out. Credit goes to a wave of lending, but economists warn that debt-fueled growth can’t continue.
docs.snippet: New figures suggest the Chinese slowdown is bottoming out. Credit goes to a wave of lending, but economists warn that debt-fueled growth can’t continue.
docs.lead_paragraph: BEIJING — China’s economy stabilized in the first three months of the year, according to official figures released on Wednesday, after Beijing flooded the financial system with money in a whatever-it-takes approach to arrest a slowdown.

headline.main: China’s Economy Stabilizes After Beijing Opens the Bank Vaults
headline.print_headline: Beijing Opened the Money Spigot Full Blast. And It Worked, for Now.
